## 2026-04-25 ƒ?" Task 3: `CommandTransaction` atomic propose-commit (v0.5.11)

**Action:** Implemented `CommandTransaction` ƒ?" a synchronous, single-use builder over `World` that buffers proposed mutations + events + precondition predicates, then on `commit()` applies everything atomically (or nothing if any precondition fails). The third and largest of the three ideas extracted from the MicropolisCore study.

**Inspiration source:** `MicropolisEngine/src/tool.h:171ƒ?"305` ƒ?" Micropolis's `ToolEffects` is the cleanest abstraction in the codebase: a tool computes a `WorldModificationsMap` (a `std::map<Position, MapValue>`) plus a cost, queues `FrontendMessage` side effects (sounds, "did tool" notifications), then `modifyIfEnoughFunding(*this, totalCost, autoBudget, recurse)` either commits the whole bundle atomically (if the player has the funds) or aborts (no map mutation, no sound, no message). For an AI-native engine where agents propose actions and the engine validates resources/preconditions, this is the natural shape: one transaction = one agent intent = one validation point = one diff entry on success.

**Branch:** `agent/command-transaction` (off `agent/overlay-layers`).

**Approach (TDD):**
1. Wrote 26 failing tests in `tests/command-transaction.test.ts` covering: basic propose-commit, multiple-mutation ordering, `mutationsApplied` count, preconditions (true/false/string return), short-circuit on first precondition failure, predicate access to live world, event buffering and emit-on-commit, aborted-transaction-no-emit, resource add/remove/cost-check pattern (success and abort cases), `setPosition` reflects in spatial grid, `removeComponent` and `patchComponent`, `abort()` lifecycle (abort-then-commit returns aborted; double-commit throws; chaining-after-commit throws), atomicity guarantees (precondition failure leaves world untouched; preconditions see baseline not proposed projection; transaction mutations all in same TickDiff when committed inside a tick), validation (`require` rejects non-function predicate; `emit` JSON-compat delegated to EventBus).
2. RED: 25/26 failed (one trivially passed by exception).
3. Implementation: `src/command-transaction.ts` exports `CommandTransaction<TEventMap>` class plus `TransactionResult` and `TransactionPrecondition` types. Internal mutation buffer is a discriminated union (`{ kind, ...payload }`). Each builder method `assertPending` + buffers entry + returns `this` for chaining. `commit()` short-circuits on first failed precondition (no mutations or events applied), otherwise replays mutations through the corresponding public `World` API (`setComponent`/`removeComponent`/etc.) so they get the same liveness/JSON-compat validation as direct calls, then emits buffered events through `EventBus`. `abort()` flips state to `aborted`; subsequent `commit()` returns `{ ok: false, code: 'aborted' }`. Single-use: after commit/abort transition, builder methods throw and second commit throws.
4. `world.transaction()` method added to `World` (one line; constructs and returns the bound `CommandTransaction`). New file exported from `src/index.ts`.
5. Test fixes during GREEN: error message changed to "CommandTransaction already committed" (was "has already been committed", which didn't match the test regex `/already (committed|aborted)/i` due to intervening "been"). Test for "all mutations in same TickDiff" updated to use `Object.keys(diff.components)` since `TickDiff.components` is keyed by component string, not an array. Two test type-narrowings to satisfy `tsc` on the discriminated union (`if (!result.ok && result.code === 'precondition_failed')` instead of `if (!result.ok)`).
