docs\reviews\full\2026-04-26\1\raw\codex.stderr.log:9630:docs/guides\systems-and-simulation.md:313:**1. Built-in `interval` field (preferred).** Set `interval: N` on the registration; the engine skips the system body on ticks where `(executingTick - 1) % interval !== intervalOffset`, where `executingTick` is the tick number being processed (equal to `world.tick + 1` while the system is running). With `interval: N` and the default `intervalOffset: 0`, the system fires on ticks 1, N+1, 2N+1, … — i.e., on the first tick and then every N. This matches the legacy `if (w.tick % N !== 0) return;` schedule exactly.
